      "description": "Daniel Erlandsson has been a long-standing Pearl drums artist across his Arch Enemy career, and by the Wages of Sin sessions in 2001–2002 his kit was firmly within the Pearl Masters / Reference family — Pearl's flagship maple shell platform of the era. The configuration follows the standard Erlandsson template: two 22\" x 18\" bass drums in a true double-kick setup (not a double pedal on a single kick), 10\" and 12\" rack toms above the kicks, and 14\" and 16\" floor toms to his right.\n\nThe maple shell character is essential to the Wages of Sin drum sound. Studio Fredman's tracking room is a controlled, relatively dry space — Fredrik Nordström's design philosophy from the mid-90s onward minimised room contribution in favour of close-mic definition. Maple shells project well in that environment: they have the tonal clarity and defined attack that translates directly to close microphones, without relying on room ambience to flesh out the sound. The result on Wages of Sin is a kit sound that reads as immediate and articulate even within the album's dense guitar production.\n\nThe double 22\" x 18\" bass drum configuration delivers the low-end foundation that Andy Sneap's production approach required. Unlike the comparatively flat-EQ'd Gothenburg drum sound of the mid-90s, Wages of Sin features a fuller, more saturated low end — modern metal mix character that Sneap brought from his work with Testament, Exodus, and the broader 2000s thrash production world. Two separate kick drums give that low end the physical impact of true double-drum stereo width, audible across the album's sustained double-kick sections on tracks like \"Ravenous\" and \"Enemy Within.\"\n\nThe 10/12/14/16 four-tom configuration is the workhorse setup for melodic death metal of this period: enough range to support melodic fills that follow guitar contours, compact enough to maintain physical efficiency at velocity. The smaller rack toms speak quickly for fast 16th-note fill content; the floor toms deliver the lower-pitched weight for section transitions and groove-oriented passages.",
