      "shell": "Brass shell with Pearl Free-Floating suspension system",
      "description": "The Pearl Free-Floating Brass 14\" x 6.5\" snare was a workhorse model for professional metal drummers in the early 2000s, and it sits at the centre of Daniel Erlandsson's snare sound on Wages of Sin. Brass shells produce a brighter, more cutting tonal character than wood or steel of comparable dimensions — exactly the quality the album's production demanded. Andy Sneap's mix philosophy on Wages of Sin produces a dense, layered guitar sound that fills more frequency space than the dry mid-90s Gothenburg template. The snare needs to cut through that density without disappearing in the mid-band, and brass shell brightness delivers that cut natively.\n\nThe 6.5\" depth produces a snare voice that balances crack and body: deeper than the shallow snare drums favoured by mid-90s death metal recordings, but not so deep that the attack slows. The Pearl Free-Floating system — in which the shell is suspended away from the lugs and the head tension is decoupled from the shell — produces additional sustain and resonance compared to standard die-cast hoop designs. On Wages of Sin, that resonance gives the snare a slightly fuller voice than the dry-cracked snare sounds of earlier Gothenburg records, fitting Sneap's more modern mix sensibility.\n\nFor Erlandsson's playing on the album, the brass snare's response at velocity is the key technical attribute. Blast beat passages on tracks like \"Behind the Smile\" and \"Snowbound\" require the drum to speak cleanly on every stroke without flamming or smearing into the next hit. Brass shells respond fast — the metallic shell character is more immediately reactive than wood — and the high-tuned head transmits each stroke with maximum definition. The combination produces blast beats that register as discrete strokes rather than buzzing washes, the production hallmark that lets Erlandsson's playing read as precise even at full velocity.",
