      "description": "Daniel Erlandsson has been a long-standing Sabian artist, and his 2002 cymbal setup for Wages of Sin draws from Sabian's professional workhorse lines: the AA series, with its bright B20 bronze attack and cutting projection, and the HH series, with its darker, hand-hammered tonal complexity. The AA/HH pairing was a standard professional metal configuration of the era — durable enough for tour-grade abuse, articulate enough for studio tracking, and tonally varied enough to give the drummer real musical range across a single recording.\n\nThe 14\" AA Rock Hi-Hats are central to the album's drum identity. Erlandsson's hi-hat work on Wages of Sin moves between driving 8th-note patterns under verse riffs, rapid 16th-note articulation in chorus and transition sections, and tight closed-hat blast accompaniment. The AA Rock weight gives the cymbals the body needed to cut through the album's dense guitar mix without disappearing — and the bright B20 character delivers the immediate stick definition that close-mic studio capture demands.\n\nThe AA crash cymbals provide the upper-frequency accent palette. The 16\" Medium Crash speaks fast and decays quickly — ideal for the rapid accent work in melodic-passage transitions. The 18\" Rock Crash delivers a fuller, more sustained crash voice for major structural moments, including the chorus entries on \"Ravenous\" and the section transitions on \"Heart of Darkness.\" Both cymbals carry the brightness needed to project above Sneap's layered guitar production without requiring heavy EQ correction in the mix.\n\nThe HH 20\" Heavy Ride provides the tonal contrast point in the setup. Where the AA crashes are bright and cutting, the HH ride delivers the darker, more complex hand-hammered character that Sabian's HH line is built around. On groove-oriented sections — the more spacious passages on \"Dead Bury Their Dead\" and the bridge on \"Behind the Smile\" — the HH ride's defined stick articulation gives Erlandsson a tonally distinct option from the brighter AA crashes, expanding the album's textural range.\n\nThe AA 18\" Mini China and AA 10\" Splash round out the accent vocabulary. China accents are essential to the Gothenburg melodic death metal idiom — the aggressive trashy character that punctuates riff changes and marks structural moments. The splash provides shorter accent texture for syncopated fill content where a full crash would be too long. Together the six-cymbal setup gives Erlandsson the full range of accent options the album's compositional density demands.",
