      "content": "The drum sound on Wages of Sin marks the transition point between two eras of Gothenburg melodic death metal production. The Studio Fredman tracking culture — close microphones, controlled room contribution, articulate drum capture — remained the foundation. But Andy Sneap's mix philosophy layered modern metal density on top: fuller low-end weight, longer snare and tom sustain, more saturated overall character. The result is a drum sound that translates well to modern playback systems and sits comfortably within the album's dense guitar arrangement, while retaining the articulate definition that the Studio Fredman tracking approach has always delivered.\n\nThe kick drum sound is heavier and more weight-forward than earlier Erlandsson recordings — Sneap's mix philosophy emphasised low-end body in a way that the mid-90s Gothenburg approach did not. The snare retains the brightness and cut that brass shell construction delivers, but with slightly more sustain in the mix than the dry-cracked snare sounds of the earlier Gothenburg template. The cymbals carry the bright AA character on top with HH ride contrast underneath, providing the textural variation that the album's compositional range demands.",
