      "shell": "Brass shell with Pearl Free-Floating suspension system",
      "description": "On Anthems of Rebellion, Daniel Erlandsson's snare work continued with his preference for the Pearl Free-Floating Brass 14\" x 6.5\" — the same fundamental approach he had used on Wages of Sin, chosen for the brightness and cut that brass shell construction delivers in dense guitar environments. The Free-Floating system's shell-isolation design — in which the shell is suspended away from the hardware — preserves sustain and resonance by decoupling the shell's vibration from mechanical dampening.\n\nIn the context of Anthems of Rebellion's production, the brass shell's cutting character is essential. The album's guitar arrangements are layered and harmonically rich, with Amott's melodic leads occupying significant mid-frequency space. A warmer, wood-shell snare would be absorbed into that mid-frequency density; the brass shell's brighter attack speaks above it, giving the snare a distinct voice in the mix even when surrounded by full-production guitar layers.\n\nThe 6.5\" depth produces the balance of crack and body that professional melodic death metal requires. Shallower snares speak fast but can sound thin in full-band contexts; deeper snares have more body but can slow the attack at velocity. The 6.5\" Free-Floating Brass sits at the practical optimum — fast enough for the blast beat passages on \"Exist to Dominate,\" full enough for the mid-tempo groove sections on \"We Will Rise.\"",
