        "question": "How does Anthems of Rebellion fit in the Arch Enemy discography and Erlandsson's career?",
        "answer": "Anthems of Rebellion (2003) is the second album in Arch Enemy's defining Angela Gossow era, following the breakthrough Wages of Sin (2002) and preceding Doomsday Machine (2005). Within Erlandsson's career arc, it represents his most compositionally sophisticated melodic death metal statement to that point — fourteen years of Gothenburg scene experience (beginning with Eucharist in 1989) expressed through arrangements where double-kick patterns articulate guitar riff rhythmic content, blast beats function as structural events rather than constant texture, and the drum kit voice has evolved to the warmer Pearl Masters MMX tonal character. The album confirmed that the Angela Gossow–era Arch Enemy was not a one-record phenomenon, establishing the creative platform that Doomsday Machine would push to its commercial peak two years later. For the next chapter: [Doomsday Machine drum setup (2005)](/articles/doomsday-machine-drum-setup). For the full discography context: [Daniel Erlandsson at MetalForge](/drummer/daniel-erlandsson)."
