      "title": "Pearl Daniel Erlandsson Signature Snare 14\" x 5.5\": The Mature Model",
      "brand": "Pearl",
      "model": "Pearl Daniel Erlandsson Signature",
      "size": "14\" x 5.5\"",
      "shell": "Co-designed signature shell construction",
      "description": "By the Rise of the Tyrant sessions, Daniel Erlandsson was playing his co-designed Pearl signature snare — a 14\" x 5.5\" model developed in collaboration with Pearl to his specific requirements for Arch Enemy's performance demands. The 5.5\" depth produces the balance between crack and body that the signature model was designed to deliver: faster-responding and brighter than a 6.5\" deep drum, fuller and more musical than a shallow 5\" model. This depth sits at the practical optimum for melodic death metal, where the snare must project through dense guitar arrangements without losing tonal identity.\n\nThe co-design relationship behind the signature snare means the drum was built to Erlandsson's specification rather than selected from Pearl's existing production catalog — a significant distinction that indicates the precision he brings to his setup choices. For Rise of the Tyrant's Andy Sneap production, where the snare voice is one of the album's defining sonic characteristics, having a drum tuned and constructed to specific requirements rather than approximated from stock models is aurally consequential.\n\nThe snare's voice on Rise of the Tyrant sits differently from the Pearl Free-Floating Brass approach of the earlier albums — the signature model's construction produces a snare character that is more controlled and musically defined, with the tonal focus that sustained blast beat passages demand. On the most intense sections of \"Revolution Begins\" and \"The Last Enemy,\" the snare speaks with the authority and clarity that marks the difference between a drummer who's managing intensity and a drummer who's commanding it.",
